                     <expan><abbr>M</abbr><ex>arco</ex></expan>
                  </name>
                  <name type="gentilicium" key="Nemonius">Nemo<hi rend="ligature">ni</hi>
                     <hi rend="small">o</hi>
                  </name>
                  <lb n="3"/>
                  <name type="cognomen" key="Theodotus">Theodoto</name>
               </persName>.
                    <lb n="4"/>
               <persName>
                  <name type="gentilicium" key="Aelia">
                     <expan><abbr>Ael</abbr><ex>ia</ex></expan>
                  </name>
                  <name type="cognomen" key="Karula">Karula</name>
               </persName> e<hi rend="small">i</hi>u<hi rend="stacked">s</hi>.</ab>
         </div>
         <div type="translation">
            <p>To the Divine Spirits. To Marcus Nemonius Theodotus. His Aelia Karula (made
               this).</p>
         </div>
         <div type="commentary">
            <p>line 4: Ael(ius) Karulaeius (Tuck), Karula eius (CIL)</p>
            <p>Tuck reads KARVLAEIVS (line 4) as one word: the cognomen "Karuleius," leading
               him to expand  AEL (line 4)  into the masculine Ael(ius). I have chosen to follow the
               reading found in the CIL, which has KARVLAEIVS as two words: the cognomen "Karula"
               and "eius." I have therefore expanded AEL as the feminine "Aelia."</p>
         </div>
